Kadane’s Algorithm finds the maximum sum contiguous subarray in:

O(n) time

O(1) extra space

It’s extremely lightweight, which makes it suitable for memory-constrained systems.
Kadane’s algorithm may be used in embedded systems for:

1️⃣ Signal Processing

Detecting bursts in sensor data

Finding maximum energy windows in vibration or audio signals

Identifying anomaly spikes

Example:
A vibration sensor on a motor controller may use a Kadane-style approach to detect the strongest continuous vibration segment.

2️⃣ Power / Energy Monitoring

Detecting peak load windows

Finding maximum power consumption intervals

3️⃣ Real-Time Data Streams

Since it:

Uses constant memory

Requires only a single pass

Has no recursion

Has minimal CPU cost

…it fits well in:

Microcontrollers (ARM Cortex-M, AVR, ESP32)

Low-memory RTOS systems

Edge IoT devices
